al_line":43,"side":"LEFT","in_reply_to_id":1874978450,"original_position":4,"position":4,"subject_type":"line"},"pull_request":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/pulls/5618","id":2221638889,"node_id":"PR_kwDOCpMuHc6Ea4Tp","html_url":"https://github.com/lfortran/lfortran/pull/5618","diff_url":"https://github.com/lfortran/lfortran/pull/5618.diff","patch_url":"https://github.com/lfortran/lfortran/pull/5618.patch","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lfortran/lfortran/issues/5618","number":5618,"state":"open","locked":false,"title":"Support full KIND specifications in IMPLICIT type declarations","user":{"login":"pjh40","id":40867327,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjQwODY3MzI3","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/40867327?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40","html_url":"https://github.com/pjh40","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/pjh40/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"body":"This PR addresses deficiencies in the parsing of `implicit_spec` rules, where kind arguments had to either be an integer or an identifier.  While it is not possible to simply use a grammar rule like:
```bison
implicit_spec
    : declaration_type_spec "(" letter_spec_list ")" {
           $$ = IMPLICIT_SPEC($1, $3, @$); }
    ;
``` 
due to essential shift/reduce conflicts in the parser, we can use `kind_arg_list` instead of `letter_spec_list`, and produce rules like:
```bison
implicit_spec
    : KW_INTEGER "(" kind_arg_list ")" "(" kind_arg_list ")" {
            $$ = IMPLICIT_SPEC(ATTR_TYPE_KIND(Integer, $3, @$), $6, @$); }
    | KW_INTEGER "*" TK_INTEGER "(" kind_arg_list ")" {
            $$ = IMPLICIT_SPEC(ATTR_TYPE_INT(Integer, $3, @$), $5, @$);
	    WARN_INTEGERSTAR($3, @2);}
    | KW_INTEGER "(" kind_arg_list ")" {
            $$ = IMPLICIT_SPEC(ATTR_TYPE(Integer, @$), $3, @$); }
    ;
```
Note that the _declaration-type-spec_ portion of the `implicit_spec` *must* be included directly in each alternative: trying to move them to another rule brings back the shift/reduce conflicts.  However, the only thing this affects is the format of warnings on Sun-style `*` declarations (e.g. `INTEGER*4`).

The basic changes are:

1.  The `ImplicitSpec` no longer contains an a `kind` description: all kind information is embedded in the Type AST.
2.  Rather than converting from letter-spec to a simplified kind, we convert from a `kind_arg` to a `letter_spec`
3. Warnings are now enabled on Sun-style declarations in implicit
4. The full `KIND` grammar is accepted for all declaration types
5. Errors in `COMPLEX*<n>` warning messages have been corrected. 


